06090nam a22009135i 9781614511458DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20122013gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)853266141  a97816145114587 a10.1515/97816145114582doi  a(DE-B1597)176265  a(OCoLC)826685182  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090002bisacsh0481pa400qDE-10104aThe Syntax of Topic, Focus, and Contrast :bAn Interface-based Approach /ced. by Ad Neeleman, Reiko Vermeulen. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2012] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (307 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Generative Grammar [SGG] ,x0167-4331 ;v11300tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tTable of Contents -- tChapter 1. The Syntactic Expression of Information Structure -- tChapter 2. Towards a Unified Encoding of Contrast and Scope -- tChapter 3. Word order variation and information structure in Japanese and Korean -- tChapter 4. Encoding focus and contrast in Russian -- tChapter 5. Against FP Analyses of Clefts -- tChapter 6. Focus movement can be destressing, but it need not be -- tChapter 7. Types of Focus and their Interaction with Negation -- tChapter 8. Concluding Remarks -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book addresses how core notions of information structure (topic, focus and contrast) are expressed in syntax. The authors propose that the syntactic effects of information structure come about as a result of mapping rules that are flexible enough to allow topics and foci to be expressed in a variety of positions, but strict enough to capture certain cross-linguistic generalisations about their distribution. In particular, the papers argue that only contrastive topics and contrastive foci undergo movement and that this is because such movement has the function of marking the scope of contrast. Several predications are derived from this proposal: such as that a focus cannot move across a topic – whether the latter is in situ or not. Syntactic and semantic evidence in support of this proposal is presented from a wide range of languages (including Dutch, English, Japanese, Korean and Russian) and theoretical consequences explored. The first chapter not only outlines its theoretical aims, but also provides an introduction to information structure. As a consequence, the book is accessible to advanced students as well as professional linguists.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aSyntax, Semantics, Information Structure.1 aKoot, Hans van de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeeleman, Ad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeeleman, Ad, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aReeve, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSzendrői, Kriszta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTitov, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVermeulen, Reiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVermeulen, Reiko, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Linguistics and Semiotics  2000-2014 (EN)z978311023845708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Linguistics and Semiotics 2000 - 2014z9783110636970oZDB-23-DLS08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter Mouton Backlist 2000-2015z978311074296